  "text": "Although surgery has been the primary treatment for pectus carinatum, surgery requires general anesthesia and may cause postoperative pain and a residual visible scar. Several reports have shown that compression bracing to correct pectus carinatum is safe, reliable, and effective. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [4] [CITATION_3] Patient compliance is the most important factor that contributes to good results with the dynamic compression orthosis. the therapy is effective when the orthosis is worn ≥15 hours per day, as confirmed in our study.",
